# CASL Authorization

This repo uses **CASL** (`@casl/ability` v6+) for every authorization decision. The role × action matrix in `docs/product/users-roles-and-permissions.md` is the spec; CASL is the implementation.

## One source of truth

All ability rules live in `@gamevine/shared`. Both apps import the **same** `defineAbilitiesFor(user)` factory. This is non-negotiable — if you're tempted to write role logic in `apps/web` or `apps/api`, stop and move it to `packages/shared`.

```ts
// packages/shared/src/abilities/abilities.ts
import { AbilityBuilder, createMongoAbility, type MongoAbility } from '@casl/ability';

export type AppAction =
  | 'manage'
  | 'create'
  | 'read'
  | 'update'
  | 'delete'
  | 'approve'
  | 'reject'
  | 'fund'
  | 'publish'
  | 'unpublish'
  | 'rollback'
  | 'suspend'
  | 'ban'
  | 'remove'
  | 'adjust';

export type AppSubject =
  | 'User'
  | 'Game'
  | 'Idea'
  | 'RoadmapItem'
  | 'Contribution'
  | 'PipelineRun'
  | 'Release'
  | 'WalletTransaction'
  | 'Report'
  | 'AuditLog'
  | 'all';

export type AppAbility = MongoAbility<[AppAction, AppSubject]>;

export interface AbilityUser {
  id: string;
  role: 'visitor' | 'free' | 'supporter' | 'creator' | 'super_admin';
  // Any additional fields needed for condition-based rules (e.g., ownedGameIds).
}

export function defineAbilitiesFor(user: AbilityUser | null): AppAbility {
  const { can, cannot, build } = new AbilityBuilder<AppAbility>(createMongoAbility);

  // Visitor / logged-out.
  can('read', 'Game');

  if (user?.role === 'super_admin') {
    can('manage', 'all');
  }

  if (user?.role === 'creator' || user?.role === 'super_admin') {
    can(['update', 'publish', 'unpublish', 'rollback'], 'Game', { ownerUserId: user.id });
  }

  // ...rest of the matrix...

  return build();
}
```

- **Subject strings, not classes.** We match against a literal subject string (e.g. `'Game'`) and, where ownership matters, pass a resource-typed object via `subject('Game', game)` so MongoDB-style conditions (`{ ownerUserId: user.id }`) evaluate.
- Use `manage` + `'all'` sparingly — only super admin should get it.
- Keep rules readable: group by role, not by subject.

## NestJS integration (`apps/api`)

There is no official `@casl/nestjs`. Follow this canonical pattern (adapted from the NestJS docs):

```ts
// apps/api/src/casl/casl-ability.factory.ts
import { Injectable } from '@nestjs/common';
import { defineAbilitiesFor, type AbilityUser, type AppAbility } from '@gamevine/shared';

@Injectable()
export class CaslAbilityFactory {
  createForUser(user: AbilityUser | null): AppAbility {
    return defineAbilitiesFor(user);
  }
}
```

```ts
// apps/api/src/casl/check-policies.decorator.ts
import { SetMetadata } from '@nestjs/common';
import type { AppAbility } from '@gamevine/shared';

export type PolicyHandler = (ability: AppAbility) => boolean;
export const CHECK_POLICIES_KEY = 'check_policy';
export const CheckPolicies = (...handlers: PolicyHandler[]) =>
  SetMetadata(CHECK_POLICIES_KEY, handlers);
```

```ts
// apps/api/src/casl/policies.guard.ts
@Injectable()
export class PoliciesGuard implements CanActivate {
  constructor(
    private readonly reflector: Reflector,
    private readonly caslFactory: CaslAbilityFactory,
  ) {}

  canActivate(ctx: ExecutionContext): boolean {
    const handlers =
      this.reflector.get<PolicyHandler[]>(CHECK_POLICIES_KEY, ctx.getHandler()) ?? [];
    const req = ctx.switchToHttp().getRequest();
    const ability = this.caslFactory.createForUser(req.user ?? null);
    return handlers.every((h) => h(ability));
  }
}
```

Usage in a controller:

```ts
@UseGuards(AuthGuard, PoliciesGuard)
@Controller('ideas')
export class IdeasController {
  @Post(':id/approve')
  @CheckPolicies((ability) => ability.can('approve', 'Idea'))
  approve(@Param('id') id: string) {
    return this.ideas.approve(id);
  }
}
```

For **ownership-scoped** actions, load the resource in the service and check `ability.can('update', subject('Game', game))`:

```ts
import { subject } from '@casl/ability';
// ...
async update(user: AbilityUser, id: string, patch: UpdateGameRequest) {
  const game = await this.games.getById(id);
  const ability = this.caslFactory.createForUser(user);
  if (!ability.can('update', subject('Game', game))) {
    throw new ForbiddenException();
  }
  // ...
}
```

## React integration (`apps/web`)

Use `@casl/react` for UI gating. The authenticated user's rules arrive from the API (`GET /me` returns `{ user, rules }` where `rules` is `ability.rules`). The web app rehydrates:

```tsx
// apps/web/src/lib/ability.ts
'use client';
import { createContext } from 'react';
import { createContextualCan, useAbility as baseUseAbility } from '@casl/react';
import { createMongoAbility } from '@casl/ability';
import type { AppAbility } from '@gamevine/shared';

export const AbilityContext = createContext<AppAbility>(createMongoAbility<AppAbility>());
export const Can = createContextualCan(AbilityContext.Consumer);
export const useAbility = () => baseUseAbility(AbilityContext);
```

Provide at the authenticated root (client component):

```tsx
// apps/web/src/app/(authenticated)/providers.tsx
'use client';
import { useMemo } from 'react';
import { createMongoAbility } from '@casl/ability';
import type { RawRuleOf } from '@casl/ability';
import type { AppAbility } from '@gamevine/shared';
import { AbilityContext } from '@/lib/ability';

export function AbilityProvider({
  rules,
  children,
}: {
  rules: RawRuleOf<AppAbility>[];
  children: React.ReactNode;
}) {
  const ability = useMemo(() => createMongoAbility<AppAbility>(rules), [rules]);
  return <AbilityContext.Provider value={ability}>{children}</AbilityContext.Provider>;
}
```

Gate UI:

```tsx
<Can I="approve" a="Idea">
  <Button onClick={approve}>Approve</Button>
</Can>

<Can I="update" this={game}>
  <EditButton />
</Can>
```

Or imperatively:

```tsx
const ability = useAbility();
if (ability.can('publish', subject('Game', game))) {
  return <PublishButton />;
}
```

## Non-negotiables

- **Client-side `Can` is a UX hint, not a gate.** Every write must be re-checked by `PoliciesGuard` on the API. If your UI gates an action the API doesn't gate, the API is wrong, fix the API.
- **No inline role checks.** `if (user.role === 'creator')` in a component or service is forbidden. Use `ability.can(...)`. If CASL can't express what you need, extend the ability definition in `@gamevine/shared`, don't work around it.
- **Single ability factory.** All rule-building happens in `defineAbilitiesFor(user)` in `@gamevine/shared`. API wraps it in `CaslAbilityFactory`; web rehydrates from serialized rules. Do not build abilities in two places.
- **Rule changes are cross-app contract changes.** Run the `schema-sync` subagent after edits to `packages/shared/src/abilities/**` — both apps depend on these types.
- **Ownership via conditions, not code branches.** Prefer `can('update', 'Game', { ownerUserId: user.id })` over building parallel runtime checks.

## Forbidden

- Importing `@casl/ability` directly in a controller or React component without going through the shared `defineAbilitiesFor` / `AbilityContext`.
- Reading `user.role` in `apps/web/src/**` or `apps/api/src/**` feature code. That logic belongs in ability rules.
- Defining abilities inside a NestJS service (they drift from the web definition). The service calls `CaslAbilityFactory.createForUser(user)`.
- Returning raw permission booleans from an API endpoint when you could return CASL rules and let the client derive them. One source, always.
- Relying on client-side `Can` for any security-sensitive action without a matching server-side `@CheckPolicies`.

